T1  - Infant-Industry Protection Reconsidered: The Case of Informational Barriers to Entry*
PY  - 1988
Y1  - 1988/11/01
DO  - 10.2307/1886074
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 103
IS  - 4
SP  - 767
EP  - 787
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - In industries with imperfect consumer information, the lack of a reputation puts latecomers at a competitive disadvantage vis-à-vis established firms. We consider whether the existence of such informational barriers to entry provides a valid reason for temporarily protecting infant producers of experience goods and services. Our model incorporates both moral hazard in an individual firm's choice of quality and adverse selection among potential entrants into the industry. We find that infant-industry protection often exacerbates the welfare loss associated with these market imperfections.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1886074
